'''Bob (Robert) T. Mason''' (born [[April 22]], [[1961]] in [[International Falls, Minnesota]]) is a retired [[United States|American]] [[ice hockey]] [[goaltender]].

A member of the 1984 U.S. Olympic Hockey Team, Mason's professional career began when he was signed as a free agent by the [[Washington Capitals]].  He had two stints with the Capitals (1984<U+2013>87 and 1989<U+2013>90).  During his first stint, he was involved in one of the longest playoff games in NHL history against the [[New York Islanders]] in [[1987]], which took four overtimes to decide the outcome.

Mason also played for the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] (1987<U+2013>88), [[Quebec Nordiques]] (1988<U+2013>89), and [[Vancouver Canucks]] (1990<U+2013>91).

Today, Mason is the goaltending coach for the [[Minnesota Wild]].  Previously, he was the goaltending coach for the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] during the first two years of the franchise's existence.

